The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Sports | India thrash Pakistan
                                                   India thrash Pakistan
            A STAFF REPORTER                      
	Calcutta: Indian women kicked off their World Cup campaign on a resounding note as they spanked arch-rivals Pakistan by 10 wickets in Bowral on Saturday.         
	Electing to field first, India shot out Pakistan for a paltry 57 in 29 overs. The Indian openers reached the target in ten overs at the Bradman Oval. Anjum Chopra and Anagha Deshpande remained unbeaten to guide India home.         
	The Indian bowlers, spearheaded by captain Jhulan Goswami, made full use of the early morning conditions.         
	Player of the Match Rumeli Dhar finished with figures of 8-5-7-3. It was an important victory for us as it was World Cup opener and against Pakistan. I am glad we have started the tournament on a winning note, Jhulan said, according to a ICC release.         
	Before the start of play, players, officials and spectators, observed a minutes silence in memory of those killed or injured during Tuesdays terror attack in Lahore.               
	England win         
	In the other match of the day, England beat Sri Lanka by 100 runs.         
	Brief Scores         
	England 277/5 (Claire Taylor 101). Sri Lanka 177/7 (Laura Marsh 3/32). England won by 100 runs.                                                                                                                       
